4 A BILL
5 TO BE ENTITLED
6 AN ACT
7
8
9 Relating to Jefferson County; to authorize the
10 Jefferson County Commission to adopt an ordinance prohibiting
11 noise disturbances in unincorporated residential areas of the
12 county; to define "noise disturbance"; and to provide for
13 collection of civil fines for violations of the ordinance.
14 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
15 Section 1. For the purposes of this act, the following
16 terms have the following meanings:
17 (1) BOUNDARY LINE. Any line that distinguishes
18 ownership or possession of real property, including a survey
19 line separating lots, or a common wall or ceiling or floor
20 within a building with more than one dwelling such as a
21 duplex, condominium, apartment, or townhouse, and extending
22 outside to any feature such as a fence, hedge, path or
23 walkway, or ditch that is shared by at least two dwellings.
24 (2) dBA. Sound level as measured by A-weighted decibel
25 units.
26 (3) NOISE DISTURBANCE. a. Any of the following
27 conditions:
28 1. When an individual plays any electronic device for
Page 1

1. When an individual plays any electronic device for
HB564 INTRODUCED
29 emitting sound in any of the following ways:
30 (i) The source of the sound is in a moving or
31 stationary vehicle, and the volume is plainly audible at a
32 distance of 25 feet or more from the source of the sound.
33 (ii) The source of the sound is on any road, street,
34 sidewalk, parking lot, park, or common area, and the volume is
35 plainly audible at a distance of 25 feet or more from the
36 source of the sound.
37 (iii) The volume is plainly audible across at least one
38 boundary line from the source of the sound.
39 2. When an individual, having the right to control the
40 source of the sound, causes or permits the sound to continue
41 for one minute or more such that the sound measures at the
42 boundary line nearest its source at the following levels:
43 (i) At 70 dBA or more between the hours of 8:00 a.m.
44 and 8:00 p.m.
45 (ii) At 50 dBA or more between the hours of 9:00 p.m.
46 and 6:00 a.m.
47 3. When an individual in control of a vehicle causes or
48 permits the sound from the vehicle to continue for one minute
49 or more such that the sound measures at 70 dBA or more at the
50 exterior of the vehicle.
51 4. When an individual in control of a vehicle that has
52 been modified to amplify or increase the sound emitted by the
53 mechanical components of the vehicle causes or permits the
54 sound to continue for one minute or more such that the sound
55 measures at 70 dBA or more in the area surrounding the
56 vehicle.
Page 2

vehicle.
HB564 INTRODUCED
57 5. When an individual, having the right to control the
58 source of the sound, causes or permits any sound between the
59 hours of 8:00 p.m. and 8:00 a.m., which is not continuous but
60 repeats at intervals within a period of at least one-half hour
61 such that a reasonable individual located across at least one
62 boundary line from the source would be disturbed in the
63 enjoyment of his or her property.
64 6. When an individual who owns or controls a dog
65 permits the dog to be outdoors and bark continuously for 10
66 minutes or more.
67 b. The term does not include any of the following sound
68 sources:
69 1. Any equipment operated by any police, fire
70 department, rescue squad, ambulance, or other emergency
71 response service.
72 2. Any school-related activity, including sound
73 incidental to the start and end of a school day, recess, bells
74 and alarms, athletic training, a band, an orchestra, a dance,
75 a concert, or a sporting event.
76 3. Any construction-related activity, including
77 demolition, excavation, filling, grading, delivery of
78 materials, operation of machinery and power equipment, and
79 building, assembly, and installation.
80 4. Any home or vehicle security system or alarm,
81 provided that the individual in control of the system or alarm
82 silences the system or alarm as soon as is reasonably
83 possible.
84 5. Any lawn mower or domestic power tool operated
Page 3

5. Any lawn mower or domestic power tool operated
HB564 INTRODUCED
85 between the hours of 6:00 a.m. and 9:00 p.m.
86 6. Any electric generator in the case of a power
87 outage.
88 7. Vehicle traffic, aircraft, and trains.
89 8. Any lawful public gathering or rally, including live
90 music or amplified sound.
91 9. Garbage and recycling collection.
92 (4) RESIDENTIAL AREA. Any real property within an area
93 that has a zoning classification beginning with 'R-'.
94 Section 2. (a) The Jefferson County Commission may
95 adopt for the residential area within Jefferson County and
96 outside of the corporate limits of any municipality an
97 ordinance that prohibits any noise disturbance in that area.
98 (b) The Jefferson County Commission may provide that a
99 violation of the ordinance shall be a public nuisance subject
100 to a civil fine, to be issued by citation by a law enforcement
101 officer or constable, of not more than two hundred dollars
102 ($200) for the first violation, not more than six hundred
103 dollars ($600) for the second violation, and not more than one
104 thousand eight hundred dollars ($1,800) for the third
105 violation.
106 (c) The civil fine shall be considered a debt owed to
107 the Jefferson County Commission when it becomes final in one
108 of the following ways:
109 (1) Thirty days after issuance of the citation, unless
110 the person cited within that period requests a due process
111 hearing challenging the validity of the citation before the
112 Jefferson County Commission or a hearing officer designated by
Page 4

Jefferson County Commission or a hearing officer designated by
HB564 INTRODUCED
113 the Jefferson County Commission.
114 (2) Thirty days after the due process hearing concludes
115 with an order upholding the validity of the citation, unless
116 the person cited within that period files an appeal in the
117 Circuit Court of Jefferson County for a hearing de novo on the
118 validity of the citation.
119 (3) Immediately upon the issuance of an order of the
120 Circuit Court of Jefferson County concluding that the citation
121 is valid.
122 (d)(1) The Jefferson County Commission may enforce a
123 final civil fine by civil action in the same manner as any
124 other debt. The individual owing the fine shall be liable for
125 all costs, including court costs and attorney fees, if a civil
126 action is necessary to collect the fine.
127 (2) The Jefferson County Commission may commence a
128 civil action in the Circuit Court of Jefferson County to abate
129 or enjoin any ongoing or persistent violation of either
130 ordinance. The person cited shall be assessed all costs of
131 abatement, including court costs and attorney fees.
132 Section 3. This act shall become effective on October
133 1, 2026.
